    {
      "turn_number": 32,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I keep thinking about the little things that make pregnancy feel real — the quiet on the Red Line, the salt marshes, and then the wave of panic about a bus fare or a co-pay. I expected friends and family to rally more, but mostly it’s been my boyfriend and me figuring out schedules, shifts, and whether we can afford extra vitamins. I thought community would mean someone to trade tips with or a neighbor offering a ride to appointments; instead most help has been practical: him timing my meds, my sister checking in by text.\n\nWhat would actually help is simple stuff: appointments that don’t mean missing work, a nurse who remembers my name, clear explanations without medical jargon, and someone asking how I’m really doing — not just whether my blood pressure is okay. I want to keep the joy in this, but the system often feels transactional. Still, I’m hopeful. When a clinician smiled today and congratulated me, it felt like seeing sunlight through clouds. That small human moment mattered more than any pamphlet.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "Q15",
      "input_tokens": 1347,
      "output_tokens": 473
    },
